1
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:09,250
[KONATA]
Okay! Let's do this!

2
00:00:09,333 --> 00:00:11,083
[TSUKASA]
Sure! Let's go!

3
00:00:11,166 --> 00:00:12,750
[KAGAMI]
Quit screwin' around and start!

4
00:00:12,833 --> 00:00:15,458
[singing in Japanese]

5
00:01:37,791 --> 00:01:40,000
Look! They bought
me a new cell phone!

6
00:01:40,083 --> 00:01:42,583
Make sure you don't put
it in the laundry this time.

7
00:01:42,666 --> 00:01:43,875
You're right.

8
00:01:43,958 --> 00:01:45,583
This time I'll keep it
where I won't forget it.

9
00:01:45,666 --> 00:01:48,375
[MATSURI] Tsukasa! Could you
help me out for a sec?

10
00:01:48,458 --> 00:01:49,666
Okay. I'm coming!

11
00:01:49,750 --> 00:01:50,791
[object thumps]

12
00:01:50,875 --> 00:01:51,875
[KAGAMI groans]

13
00:01:51,958 --> 00:01:54,166
[crying]

14
00:01:57,708 --> 00:01:59,375
--Ba...
--[phone beeping]

15
00:02:00,666 --> 00:02:01,666
l...

16
00:02:03,750 --> 00:02:04,791
[KAGAMI sighs]

17
00:02:04,875 --> 00:02:06,000
...sa...

18
00:02:06,083 --> 00:02:07,583
Irritated,
irritated, irritated...

19
00:02:07,666 --> 00:02:09,041
--...mic.
--...irritated, irritated.

20
00:02:09,125 --> 00:02:10,666
--Vine...
--Super irritated.

21
00:02:10,750 --> 00:02:12,208
--...gar!
--Really, really irritated!

22
00:02:12,291 --> 00:02:14,375
Ah! That's
really irritating!

23
00:02:14,458 --> 00:02:16,541
Just type it in already
or let me do it!

24
00:02:16,625 --> 00:02:18,750
[grunts]
No, thanks. I'm okay.

25
00:02:18,833 --> 00:02:20,500
I can do it myself.

26
00:02:22,666 --> 00:02:23,916
I'm here to hang out!

27
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:25,875
Hey! Come on in, Onee-san.

28
00:02:25,958 --> 00:02:27,458
Whatcha playin' there?

29
00:02:27,541 --> 00:02:29,500
It's a dating sim
that just came out.

30
00:02:29,583 --> 00:02:30,583
Huh.

31
00:02:33,916 --> 00:02:35,166
I think I'm gonna pick a manga

32
00:02:35,250 --> 00:02:36,750
and read that for a while.

33
00:02:36,833 --> 00:02:38,333
Okay.

34
00:02:38,416 --> 00:02:41,500
[thinks] Uh-oh. This game's
got an age restriction.

35
00:02:41,583 --> 00:02:43,541
Either she doesn't
know or she does,

36
00:02:43,625 --> 00:02:45,500
but she's letting it slide.

37
00:02:45,583 --> 00:02:48,125
Okay. Come on, Officer,
which one is it?

38
00:02:48,208 --> 00:02:50,875
Get this. We're having
traffic safety week, right?

39
00:02:50,958 --> 00:02:52,958
So we're taking in people
like there's no tomorrow.

40
00:02:53,041 --> 00:02:54,666
--Huh.
--They're making us run

41
00:02:54,750 --> 00:02:55,916
a check on every little thing,

42
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:57,833
and we gotta explain
all the traffic laws.

43
00:02:57,916 --> 00:02:59,916
It's a big-time
pain in the butt if you ask me.

44
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:02,125
And the people even get mad
at me for doing it!

45
00:03:02,208 --> 00:03:03,750
[KONATA thinks]
Knowing you and how you act,

46
00:03:03,833 --> 00:03:05,666
how's anyone supposed
to take you seriously

47
00:03:05,750 --> 00:03:07,250
about laws and safety?

48
00:03:07,333 --> 00:03:09,166
Can you believe it?
I sure can't!

49
00:03:12,916 --> 00:03:15,125
[MIYUKI thinks] I hear the cold
that's been going around now

50
00:03:15,208 --> 00:03:16,666
is lasting a long time.

51
00:03:16,750 --> 00:03:19,000
I need to get better, fast.

52
00:03:19,083 --> 00:03:21,375
According to the number
I've taken,

53
00:03:21,458 --> 00:03:24,041
it looks as though
I'll be here for a while.

54
00:03:24,125 --> 00:03:27,041
I'll just read a book
until I'm called.

55
00:03:27,125 --> 00:03:29,375
[RECEPTIONIST]
Mr. Ando! Mr. Shigeo Ando!

56
00:03:29,458 --> 00:03:31,583
[MAN grunts]

57
00:03:36,875 --> 00:03:40,208
[RECEPTIONIST]
Ms. Takara! Ms. Miyuki Takara!

58
00:03:42,875 --> 00:03:46,375
Ms. Takara! Is there
a Ms. Takara here?

59
00:03:49,541 --> 00:03:52,416
Okay. Is Ms. Mariko
Nishiyama here?

60
00:03:57,791 --> 00:03:59,041
[sighs]

61
00:03:59,125 --> 00:04:00,416
[gasps, thinks] Huh?

62
00:04:00,500 --> 00:04:01,708
What? Did they call me?

63
00:04:01,791 --> 00:04:03,291
What time is it? Oh no!

64
00:04:03,375 --> 00:04:06,666
I need to pay more attention
to my surroundings.

65
00:04:08,666 --> 00:04:11,958
[BUS ANNOUNCER] Coming up
is Kamata, our last stop.

66
00:04:12,041 --> 00:04:14,333
[thinks]
Huh? Oh, no! It happened again!

67
00:04:14,416 --> 00:04:15,541
Where am I?

68
00:04:15,625 --> 00:04:17,708
But in the end I still
had to show Tsukasa

69
00:04:17,791 --> 00:04:19,750
how to send text messages
with her phone.

70
00:04:19,833 --> 00:04:21,541
Even after messaging
with it so much

71
00:04:21,625 --> 00:04:23,125
she told me she never
figured it out.

72
00:04:23,208 --> 00:04:24,833
--Really?
--Oh, yeah!

73
00:04:24,916 --> 00:04:26,208
And now that she knows
how it's done,

74
00:04:26,291 --> 00:04:27,958
she's been texting me non-stop

75
00:04:28,041 --> 00:04:29,833
with anything and
everything she can think of.

76
00:04:29,916 --> 00:04:32,166
It's gotta suck
to be on the receiving end

77
00:04:32,250 --> 00:04:33,375
of all of those texts, though.

78
00:04:33,458 --> 00:04:34,750
--No, not really.
--[cell phone buzzes]

79
00:04:34,833 --> 00:04:36,083
I mean, I'm not
gonna lose any sleep

80
00:04:36,166 --> 00:04:37,333
worrying about it. You know?

81
00:04:37,416 --> 00:04:38,791
Here's the thing.

82
00:04:38,875 --> 00:04:40,500
At first she gets really
excited about stuff,

83
00:04:40,583 --> 00:04:42,041
but then she'll get
bored and move on.

84
00:04:42,125 --> 00:04:43,500
Yeah. I know what you mean.

85
00:04:43,583 --> 00:04:45,500
Some people can be
so childish sometimes.

86
00:04:45,583 --> 00:04:46,750
Uh! I got another.

87
00:04:46,833 --> 00:04:48,125
If she doesn't get bored soon,

88
00:04:48,208 --> 00:04:49,958
you're gonna be hating life.

89
00:04:50,041 --> 00:04:52,958
Wait. She can't have that
much stuff to text you about.

90
00:04:53,041 --> 00:04:55,541
I know. And we're together
all the time anyway.

91
00:04:55,625 --> 00:04:57,750
Oh! And she just
discovered emoticons.

92
00:04:57,833 --> 00:04:59,291
You see?

93
00:04:59,375 --> 00:05:01,500
"You wanna buy the soy
milk cream buns again

94
00:05:01,583 --> 00:05:03,125
on our way home today?"

95
00:05:03,208 --> 00:05:06,208
Hm? What's all that
supposed to mean?

96
00:05:06,291 --> 00:05:07,708
I don't know if you can tell,

97
00:05:07,791 --> 00:05:09,708
but she's really having fun
with emoticons.

98
00:05:09,791 --> 00:05:12,041
Might as well
be hieroglyphics.

99
00:05:12,125 --> 00:05:14,208
[cell phone rings]

100
00:05:14,291 --> 00:05:16,208
Mmm?

101
00:05:16,291 --> 00:05:19,041
Huh. Looks like she
got used to doing it.

102
00:05:19,125 --> 00:05:21,875
[keypad dialing]

103
00:05:23,500 --> 00:05:25,041
--[cell phone rings]
--Hm?

104
00:05:27,083 --> 00:05:28,708
--[television audience laughter]
--[cell phone rings]

105
00:05:28,791 --> 00:05:29,750
[grunts]

106
00:05:31,041 --> 00:05:32,041
[sighs]

107
00:05:32,125 --> 00:05:33,500
--[cell phone rings]
--Huh?

108
00:05:34,708 --> 00:05:37,416
--[gulping]
--[cell phone rings]

109
00:05:38,791 --> 00:05:39,875
[cell phone rings]

110
00:05:39,958 --> 00:05:41,291
[grumbles]

111
00:05:41,375 --> 00:05:42,541
[keypad dialing]

112
00:05:42,625 --> 00:05:44,125
--Okay.
--Oh, jeez!

113
00:05:44,208 --> 00:05:46,166
I get you're having
fun with it and stuff,

114
00:05:46,250 --> 00:05:48,458
but you think you could text
someone else for a change?

115
00:05:48,541 --> 00:05:50,625
Hey.
You guys got a minute?

116
00:05:50,708 --> 00:05:51,625
Sure.

117
00:05:51,708 --> 00:05:53,250
Well, I can't seem
to figure out

118
00:05:53,333 --> 00:05:55,208
how to send these
text message things

119
00:05:55,291 --> 00:05:57,250
--from my phone.
--[TSUKASA thinks] For real?

120
00:05:57,333 --> 00:05:59,291
Oh, Dad. That's super easy.

121
00:05:59,375 --> 00:06:01,291
Can't believe you don't know.

122
00:06:01,375 --> 00:06:03,333
Okay. I'll totally
teach you how.

123
00:06:03,416 --> 00:06:05,791
Isn't it funny how
people learn something new

124
00:06:05,875 --> 00:06:08,333
then run out and brag about
how much of an expert they are?

125
00:06:08,416 --> 00:06:09,958
Uh, yeah.

126
00:06:10,041 --> 00:06:11,666
[laughs]

127
00:06:11,750 --> 00:06:14,500
There just aren't words
to describe that hard stench.

128
00:06:14,583 --> 00:06:16,458
[KAGAMI]
I know. It stinks so bad.

129
00:06:16,541 --> 00:06:18,166
--[TSUKASA giggles] Yeah.
--[KONATA thinks] Huh?

130
00:06:18,250 --> 00:06:20,666
Wow. You sure got a lot of
people in your address book.

131
00:06:20,750 --> 00:06:23,000
--Don't ya?
-Hey! Don't look without asking!

132
00:06:23,083 --> 00:06:25,583
You got stuff you don't want
anyone to see or somethin'?

133
00:06:25,666 --> 00:06:27,833
Not really.
You just don't do that.

134
00:06:27,916 --> 00:06:30,458
It's a guy, right?
It's totally a guy!

135
00:06:30,541 --> 00:06:32,125
No! It isn't a guy!

136
00:06:32,208 --> 00:06:34,500
[cell phone ringing]

137
00:06:35,625 --> 00:06:36,958
[sighs]

138
00:06:37,041 --> 00:06:38,750
She's not picking up
her cell phone.

139
00:06:38,833 --> 00:06:40,375
Guess I'll try
calling the house.

140
00:06:40,458 --> 00:06:42,916
[beeps]

141
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:44,333
[cell phone rings]

142
00:06:44,416 --> 00:06:45,916
[KONATA]
Hello, Kagami!

143
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:47,583
Hey, Konata?

144
00:06:47,666 --> 00:06:49,333
You know. It'd be awesome
if you could answer

145
00:06:49,416 --> 00:06:50,958
your cell once in a while.

146
00:06:51,041 --> 00:06:53,125
Yeah. Sorry 'bout that.
The ringer's turned off,

147
00:06:53,208 --> 00:06:54,875
so I didn't know
you were calling me.

148
00:06:54,958 --> 00:06:56,791
[KAGAMI]
It's pointless to have a cell

149
00:06:56,875 --> 00:06:58,833
if you never know
anyone's calling.

150
00:06:58,916 --> 00:07:00,541
[KONATA] Where the heck
is that thing anyway?

151
00:07:00,625 --> 00:07:02,125
[KAGAMI]
See what I'm saying?

152
00:07:02,208 --> 00:07:04,291
There's no point
in you even having one.

153
00:07:04,375 --> 00:07:05,708
Yeah.
So, anyway, I wanted

154
00:07:05,791 --> 00:07:07,458
to ask you about
this coming weekend.

155
00:07:07,541 --> 00:07:09,791
[KONATA] Wait. Hang on.
Dad's calling me.

156
00:07:09,875 --> 00:07:11,708
[SOJIRO] Come on.
What's the deal? Hurry up!

157
00:07:11,791 --> 00:07:13,583
[KONATA] I'll be there
in a minute! Jeez.

158
00:07:13,666 --> 00:07:15,000
[SOJIRO] You've been
on the phone forever.

159
00:07:15,083 --> 00:07:16,625
--Come on!
--[KONATA] All right! Sorry!

160
00:07:16,708 --> 00:07:19,208
Dad just chewed me up
for being on the phone too long.

161
00:07:19,291 --> 00:07:20,583
Oh, sorry.

162
00:07:20,666 --> 00:07:22,958
I sorta always pictured
your place to be kinda chill

163
00:07:23,041 --> 00:07:24,083
when it came to stuff like that.

164
00:07:24,166 --> 00:07:25,958
I guess
it's pretty strict, huh?

165
00:07:26,041 --> 00:07:27,625
[KONATA] Nah. We're just
in the middle of playing

166
00:07:27,708 --> 00:07:29,291
a cool fighting game, is all.

167
00:07:29,375 --> 00:07:32,208
Ugh! Why didn't you say
anything about that before?

168
00:07:36,041 --> 00:07:37,375
Whether they're old or new,

169
00:07:37,458 --> 00:07:40,208
point cards have
magical powers in here.

170
00:07:40,291 --> 00:07:42,291
And then, before
I know what's happening

171
00:07:42,375 --> 00:07:44,250
I'm buying all this stuff
I never planned on.

172
00:07:44,333 --> 00:07:46,583
But you never plan
on anything anyway.

173
00:07:46,666 --> 00:07:48,500
I get what you're
coming from, though.

174
00:07:54,166 --> 00:07:55,583
She's here!

175
00:07:55,666 --> 00:07:56,708
In this city you've got...

176
00:07:56,791 --> 00:07:58,125
...Ani-- and G--mers

177
00:07:58,208 --> 00:07:59,333
She comes into our store,

178
00:07:59,416 --> 00:08:00,916
buys something,
then goes to the other shop

179
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:02,708
to buy the same thing again!

180
00:08:02,791 --> 00:08:05,375
She's the one known
as Legendary Girl "A"!

181
00:08:06,833 --> 00:08:08,000
Heh.

182
00:08:08,083 --> 00:08:09,333
[yells]

183
00:08:09,416 --> 00:08:13,125
Legendary Girl "A"
shift assemble!

184
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:18,916
[grunts]

185
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:21,000
[yells]

186
00:08:21,083 --> 00:08:22,125
[ALL]
Yeah!

187
00:08:25,875 --> 00:08:28,208
Welcome to the store!

188
00:08:28,291 --> 00:08:33,958
We've got the "Haruhi"
Volume 5 DVD in stock!

189
00:08:34,041 --> 00:08:35,958
Limited Edition!
Standard Edition!

190
00:08:36,041 --> 00:08:38,000
We've got 'em both! Oh, yeah!

191
00:08:38,083 --> 00:08:39,916
So, you want more stuff?

192
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:42,875
We've got stuff coming
in all the time!

193
00:08:42,958 --> 00:08:44,125
[thinks]
Yes, that's right.

194
00:08:44,208 --> 00:08:46,166
Show her everything we've got.

195
00:08:46,250 --> 00:08:47,541
The whole store.

196
00:08:47,625 --> 00:08:50,541
She's gonna clean the place out.
I can feel it.

197
00:08:50,625 --> 00:08:53,250
Whoops. I was looking for
the Limited Edition bookmark

198
00:08:53,333 --> 00:08:56,041
from Aquarian Age.
I gotta go Gamers.

199
00:08:56,125 --> 00:08:57,416
[shift team crying]

200
00:08:57,500 --> 00:08:58,750
This sucks!

201
00:08:58,833 --> 00:08:59,916
[yawns]

202
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:01,750
[GIRLS]
"Lucky Star."

203
00:09:01,833 --> 00:09:03,083
Awesome!

204
00:09:03,166 --> 00:09:04,458
We'll have
a sleepover this weekend

205
00:09:04,541 --> 00:09:06,250
--and play games all night.
--Cool.

206
00:09:08,250 --> 00:09:09,791
Whenever we do
this kinda stuff,

207
00:09:09,875 --> 00:09:11,166
it's always gotta
be at our house.

208
00:09:11,250 --> 00:09:13,416
--How come we never go to yours?
--Huh?

209
00:09:13,500 --> 00:09:15,291
I'd just like to
see where you live.

210
00:09:15,375 --> 00:09:16,541
Hmm...

211
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:20,083
It's not that you can't
come over to my house.

212
00:09:20,166 --> 00:09:21,750
The reason I don't invite you

213
00:09:21,833 --> 00:09:23,958
is 'cause my dad's always home
on account of his job.

214
00:09:24,041 --> 00:09:25,250
Oh. That makes sense.

215
00:09:25,333 --> 00:09:26,541
Mm-hmm. Besides.

216
00:09:26,625 --> 00:09:27,958
I don't wanna be
held responsible

217
00:09:28,041 --> 00:09:29,166
if anything happens, you know?

218
00:09:29,250 --> 00:09:30,458
--No, I don't.
--[whimpers]

219
00:09:32,166 --> 00:09:34,000
I'm kinda looking
forward to seeing

220
00:09:34,083 --> 00:09:35,666
what's Konata's house is like.

221
00:09:36,916 --> 00:09:38,291
Hey!

222
00:09:38,375 --> 00:09:40,041
Hi, guys. Come on in.

223
00:09:40,125 --> 00:09:41,708
[KAGAMI] Thanks
for letting us stay the night.

224
00:09:41,791 --> 00:09:42,791
We won't be any trouble.

225
00:09:42,875 --> 00:09:44,083
Oh! It's my pleasure.

226
00:09:44,166 --> 00:09:45,833
I've heard so much
about you guys.

227
00:09:45,916 --> 00:09:47,166
Like that you live in a shrine

228
00:09:47,250 --> 00:09:48,625
and that you're a couple
of shrine maidens.

229
00:09:48,708 --> 00:09:50,250
[KAGAMI thinks]
What's she been telling him!

230
00:09:50,333 --> 00:09:52,333
Ew! And this is
the first thing he asks?

231
00:09:52,416 --> 00:09:54,000
Here it is!

232
00:09:54,083 --> 00:09:57,916
[TSUKASA]
Wow! Look at Kona-chan's room!

233
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:00,666
I gotta hand it to ya.
You're room's amazing.

234
00:10:00,750 --> 00:10:03,500
Oh! She's so cute!

235
00:10:03,583 --> 00:10:06,000
[sighs]

236
00:10:06,083 --> 00:10:08,083
Where does this go?

237
00:10:08,166 --> 00:10:10,166
Don't tell me.
You don't want me to open this

238
00:10:10,250 --> 00:10:11,916
'cause it's where you
keep all the crazy junk

239
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:13,708
you're too embarrassed
to put on display.

240
00:10:13,791 --> 00:10:16,041
Go ahead and open
it if you want. I don't care.

241
00:10:16,125 --> 00:10:17,541
If you're lookin' for
all my weird stuff

242
00:10:17,625 --> 00:10:19,166
I usually keep it down
in my dad's study.

243
00:10:19,250 --> 00:10:21,041
I share it with him.

244
00:10:21,125 --> 00:10:23,791
Uh. You guys share it?

245
00:10:23,875 --> 00:10:25,708
Didn't you say
your dad was writer

246
00:10:25,791 --> 00:10:27,250
or something like that?

247
00:10:27,333 --> 00:10:29,666
--Yep.
--I bet you probably get hooked

248
00:10:29,750 --> 00:10:32,000
on the light novels
and dating sims your Dad writes.

249
00:10:32,083 --> 00:10:33,625
--Don't you?
--Oh, yeah.

250
00:10:33,708 --> 00:10:35,958
Well, actually, my dad doesn't
write that kinda stuff.

251
00:10:36,041 --> 00:10:37,666
--Oh, really?
--Yep.

252
00:10:37,750 --> 00:10:39,750
Huh. I didn't expect that.

253
00:10:39,833 --> 00:10:42,083
Well, I mean. Since he's a fan
of stuff like that,

254
00:10:42,166 --> 00:10:44,041
wouldn't he wanna write
those kinds of stories?

255
00:10:44,125 --> 00:10:46,041
No. My dad's
kinda like a lurker.

256
00:10:46,125 --> 00:10:48,000
He told me he didn't
wanna write that stuff,

257
00:10:48,083 --> 00:10:49,541
because he felt that,
since his real life

258
00:10:49,625 --> 00:10:51,708
was kinda like one
of those nurturing sims,

259
00:10:51,791 --> 00:10:54,083
he didn't wanna write
about it and live it too.

260
00:10:55,625 --> 00:10:57,916
[KAGAMI thinks] Ever since
I got here, it's been weird.

261
00:10:58,000 --> 00:10:59,458
Yep. That's the Izumis.

262
00:10:59,541 --> 00:11:01,041
[video game noises]

263
00:11:01,125 --> 00:11:02,500
So, get this.

264
00:11:02,583 --> 00:11:04,916
The other day, my dad was
being all clingy and stuff.

265
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:06,500
--Yeah?
--So I'm all,

266
00:11:06,583 --> 00:11:09,041
"You're actin' like an ass,"
just to see what he'd do.

267
00:11:09,125 --> 00:11:11,625
Ugh! How can you talk
to your dad like that?

268
00:11:11,708 --> 00:11:14,541
Yeah, well, after I said it,
Dad suggested I say,

269
00:11:14,625 --> 00:11:16,291
"I hate you, Dad,"
or somethin'.

270
00:11:16,375 --> 00:11:18,291
Yeah. I'm not sure
about that either.

271
00:11:18,375 --> 00:11:20,375
[groans]
That's the point.

272
00:11:20,458 --> 00:11:22,208
I don't think you
appreciate the complexity

273
00:11:22,291 --> 00:11:24,041
of my dad's way of
thinking, Kagami.

274
00:11:24,125 --> 00:11:26,000
Whatever.
You totally lost me.

275
00:11:26,083 --> 00:11:27,458
[TV playing Japanese pop]

276
00:11:27,541 --> 00:11:29,583
[yawns]

277
00:11:29,666 --> 00:11:33,375
How 'bout we take
a little break?

278
00:11:33,458 --> 00:11:35,333
--It's here!
--[TV audience applause]

279
00:11:35,416 --> 00:11:36,958
Have you noticed lately,

280
00:11:37,041 --> 00:11:39,208
how there's been a lot
of 2chan speak on TV?

281
00:11:39,291 --> 00:11:40,125
What's up with that?

282
00:11:40,208 --> 00:11:41,416
Oh. There has?

283
00:11:41,500 --> 00:11:43,791
I wouldn't know
about that stuff.

284
00:11:43,875 --> 00:11:45,750
--[bell dings]
--That's right!

285
00:11:45,833 --> 00:11:48,041
I just realized you're
this hard-core otaku,

286
00:11:48,125 --> 00:11:49,583
but I've never heard
you talk like that.

287
00:11:49,666 --> 00:11:52,458
I don't normally.

288
00:11:52,541 --> 00:11:54,583
But if I'm online
I talk like this.

289
00:11:54,666 --> 00:11:56,000
[surprised gasps]

290
00:11:56,083 --> 00:11:58,041
[KAGAMI] Whoa.
Is that really Japanese?

291
00:11:58,125 --> 00:12:00,708
[KONATA thinks] I think I've
failed if anybody can read it.

292
00:12:00,791 --> 00:12:01,958
[knife chops]

293
00:12:02,041 --> 00:12:04,458
[whimpers]

294
00:12:04,541 --> 00:12:06,458
You want me to
help with anything?

295
00:12:06,541 --> 00:12:08,375
Sure. Do you wanna
serve the salad for me?

296
00:12:08,458 --> 00:12:09,500
Mm-hmm!

297
00:12:11,083 --> 00:12:12,250
[BOTH]
Huh?

298
00:12:12,333 --> 00:12:14,166
[ALL]
Thank you for the food!

299
00:12:16,208 --> 00:12:17,291
Yummy!

300
00:12:17,375 --> 00:12:18,833
Yeah, you're right.

301
00:12:18,916 --> 00:12:20,625
This stuff tastes amazing!

302
00:12:20,708 --> 00:12:22,416
Whippin' up stuff like
this isn't a big deal

303
00:12:22,500 --> 00:12:23,958
if you do your chores.

304
00:12:24,041 --> 00:12:25,708
If you helped out
in the kitchen more, Kagami,

305
00:12:25,791 --> 00:12:27,375
you'd cook like this too.

306
00:12:27,458 --> 00:12:29,583
I don't need your advice.

307
00:12:29,666 --> 00:12:31,541
Konata look! This is perfect!

308
00:12:31,625 --> 00:12:33,125
Huh?

309
00:12:33,208 --> 00:12:35,083
I always dreamed something
like this would happen

310
00:12:35,166 --> 00:12:36,833
and it has!

311
00:12:36,916 --> 00:12:37,750
[SISTERS]
Huh?

312
00:12:37,833 --> 00:12:39,166
--Oh, yeah.
--[crying]

313
00:12:39,250 --> 00:12:40,208
So, this is what's known

314
00:12:40,291 --> 00:12:41,500
as the three high school girls

315
00:12:41,583 --> 00:12:43,291
having dinner with
a guy scenario.

316
00:12:43,375 --> 00:12:45,083
And if you ask me,
even for dating sims,

317
00:12:45,166 --> 00:12:46,916
it's freakishly overused.

318
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:48,250
That's, well...

319
00:12:51,875 --> 00:12:54,791
Doesn't it feel like
evenings are getting colder?

320
00:12:54,875 --> 00:12:57,458
Maybe I shoulda
brought a jacket with me.

321
00:12:58,791 --> 00:13:00,958
Look! A shooting star!

322
00:13:02,083 --> 00:13:03,125
Huh?

323
00:13:05,375 --> 00:13:06,958
Darn.

324
00:13:07,041 --> 00:13:08,791
Tried, but I couldn't
make my wish three times.

325
00:13:08,875 --> 00:13:10,416
When they come out
of nowhere like that,

326
00:13:10,500 --> 00:13:12,333
it's kinda hard.

327
00:13:12,416 --> 00:13:13,791
But someday I'll do it!

328
00:13:13,875 --> 00:13:15,125
I'll wish fast enough,

329
00:13:15,208 --> 00:13:16,750
and then it'll grant me a wish!

330
00:13:16,833 --> 00:13:19,041
You'll always be
a dreamer, Tsukasa.

331
00:13:19,125 --> 00:13:21,000
Too bad stuff like
that's impossible

332
00:13:21,083 --> 00:13:22,166
when you stop
to think about it.

333
00:13:22,250 --> 00:13:23,208
[BOTH] Huh?

334
00:13:23,291 --> 00:13:24,833
Whoever came up
with it knew no one

335
00:13:24,916 --> 00:13:26,708
could say their wish fast
enough for it to work.

336
00:13:26,791 --> 00:13:30,208
This one has absolutely
no dreams whatsoever.

337
00:13:30,291 --> 00:13:32,375
Are either of you guys thirsty?

338
00:13:32,458 --> 00:13:34,166
Whoa!
Thank you.

339
00:13:34,250 --> 00:13:35,750
You switched hairdos.

340
00:13:35,833 --> 00:13:37,541
Yeah. What do you think?

341
00:13:37,625 --> 00:13:39,916
We did it for fun
after we took our bath.

342
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:42,125
[KONATA thinks] Hmm. Isn't it
funny how the vibe you get

343
00:13:42,208 --> 00:13:43,708
from something on one person

344
00:13:43,791 --> 00:13:45,958
is different when
it's on someone else?

345
00:13:46,041 --> 00:13:48,500
Oh! A photo album!
Can I look at it?

346
00:13:48,583 --> 00:13:50,000
Sure, go ahead.

347
00:13:50,083 --> 00:13:52,458
Wow! You're so cute, Kona-chan!

348
00:13:52,541 --> 00:13:53,875
You haven't changed at all.

349
00:13:53,958 --> 00:13:55,791
How old are you
supposed be in this?

350
00:13:55,875 --> 00:13:57,708
It's a cool shot.

351
00:13:57,791 --> 00:13:59,708
I guess you and your dad
are pretty close, huh?

352
00:13:59,791 --> 00:14:02,333
[KONATA] Hmm? Oh!
No. That's my mom!

353
00:14:02,416 --> 00:14:03,875
[KAGAMI thinks]
She's a kid! I mean, so young!

354
00:14:03,958 --> 00:14:05,083
Don't we look alike?

355
00:14:05,166 --> 00:14:06,791
[KAGAMI thinks]
Yeah, like jailbait.

356
00:14:06,875 --> 00:14:08,291
Every time I look at Dad

357
00:14:08,375 --> 00:14:10,625
--I just can't help thinkin'.
--What?

358
00:14:10,708 --> 00:14:12,666
What part of my dad did
my mom find so attractive

359
00:14:12,750 --> 00:14:14,541
that she'd wanna marry him?

360
00:14:14,625 --> 00:14:16,041
[KAGAMI]
It's crazy how much you

361
00:14:16,125 --> 00:14:18,208
and your mom look alike, though.

362
00:14:18,291 --> 00:14:20,541
Do you like the same
type of guy as your mom?

363
00:14:20,625 --> 00:14:22,166
What is your type, anyway?

364
00:14:22,250 --> 00:14:23,541
What's my type?

365
00:14:23,625 --> 00:14:25,125
[sighs]

366
00:14:25,208 --> 00:14:27,041
I don't know. I don't
think I have one.

367
00:14:27,125 --> 00:14:30,333
--Oh. Come on! You can tell me.
--Wait!

368
00:14:30,416 --> 00:14:33,041
Mom said that her and Dad
were childhood friends first.

369
00:14:33,125 --> 00:14:34,583
I don't think my mom
was very picky

370
00:14:34,666 --> 00:14:36,375
about the guy she liked.

371
00:14:36,458 --> 00:14:38,125
Maybe that's a little harsh.

372
00:14:38,208 --> 00:14:40,250
I bet she picked him
'cause she felt sorry for him.

373
00:14:40,333 --> 00:14:42,375
Even with your parents,
you're brutal.

374
00:14:42,458 --> 00:14:44,333
You know, lookin'
at this picture of Mom's

375
00:14:44,416 --> 00:14:46,375
--got me thinkin'.
--Mm-hmm?

376
00:14:46,458 --> 00:14:48,250
These days you've got
characters in manga and games,

377
00:14:48,333 --> 00:14:50,333
like junior high kids,
who seem really mature,

378
00:14:50,416 --> 00:14:52,416
but the adults all act immature.

379
00:14:52,500 --> 00:14:54,708
What's up with that?

380
00:14:54,791 --> 00:14:56,500
[KAGAMI thinks]
Yeah, so?

381
00:14:56,583 --> 00:14:58,916
You waiting for me to whip out
a snide remark or something?

382
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:01,875
It's too bad Yuki-chan
couldn't come over tonight.

383
00:15:01,958 --> 00:15:03,666
Yeah. She had
stuff to do, though.

384
00:15:03,750 --> 00:15:05,583
I know! I'll text Yuki-chan.

385
00:15:05,666 --> 00:15:07,458
That way
she won't feel left out!

386
00:15:07,541 --> 00:15:09,041
Maybe you shouldn't bug her.

387
00:15:09,125 --> 00:15:11,458
Miyuki's probably
busy doing something.

388
00:15:11,541 --> 00:15:13,875
--[cell phone message alert]
--That was quick.

389
00:15:13,958 --> 00:15:15,875
"Glad to hear you're
all having fun.

390
00:15:15,958 --> 00:15:18,000
"Right now, I'm working
hard and doing my best

391
00:15:18,083 --> 00:15:20,333
"to finish my homework
for the weekend.

392
00:15:20,416 --> 00:15:22,250
If you do it again,
I'll make sure to..."

393
00:15:24,166 --> 00:15:26,625
I totally forgot
we had homework to do!

394
00:15:26,708 --> 00:15:28,708
Don't just sit there, Kagami.
Do something!

395
00:15:28,791 --> 00:15:29,958
[KAGAMI]
I didn't have any homework.

396
00:15:30,041 --> 00:15:31,166
Can I go to sleep now?

397
00:15:31,250 --> 00:15:32,708
No! Wait!

398
00:15:32,791 --> 00:15:36,000
-Oh! Remember the shooting star?
--Yeah?

399
00:15:36,083 --> 00:15:38,916
Maybe if I made shorter wishes
I can get them to come true.

400
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:41,083
I don't know about that.

401
00:15:42,375 --> 00:15:43,916
What you doin' over there?

402
00:15:44,000 --> 00:15:45,458
I'm trying to figure out
if there's a way

403
00:15:45,541 --> 00:15:47,208
to say my wishes faster.

404
00:15:47,291 --> 00:15:48,958
Stop running away
from reality.

405
00:15:49,041 --> 00:15:50,625
Hurry up and finish it.

406
00:15:52,541 --> 00:15:54,000
[TSUKASA]
Hey, Yuki-chan.

407
00:15:54,083 --> 00:15:56,458
I didn't really understand
this part today.

408
00:15:56,541 --> 00:15:58,041
Can you show me how it's done?

409
00:15:58,125 --> 00:16:00,125
[sighs]
Sure, I'd be glad to.

410
00:16:00,208 --> 00:16:02,208
Kona-chan comes from Konata.

411
00:16:02,291 --> 00:16:04,291
Yuki-chan comes from Miyuki.

412
00:16:04,375 --> 00:16:06,000
Hmm...

413
00:16:06,083 --> 00:16:07,791
Hey, Tsukasa,
what kind of nickname

414
00:16:07,875 --> 00:16:10,750
would you give Kagami?
Kaga-chan? Gami-chan?

415
00:16:10,833 --> 00:16:12,500
Uh. Hmm.

416
00:16:12,583 --> 00:16:14,083
Kyou-chan might be good.

417
00:16:14,166 --> 00:16:15,958
Kyou is another
way to say Kagami.

418
00:16:16,041 --> 00:16:17,791
Ah! That's a good call.

419
00:16:17,875 --> 00:16:19,083
It's perfect 'cause it reflects

420
00:16:19,166 --> 00:16:20,541
her tough-as-nails personality.

421
00:16:20,625 --> 00:16:22,791
It could also work
with this Kyou-chan.

422
00:16:22,875 --> 00:16:26,583
But that's not what I meant when
I said it. Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.

423
00:16:26,666 --> 00:16:28,125
I think it's best
we don't mention this

424
00:16:28,208 --> 00:16:29,583
to sis, you know?

425
00:16:29,666 --> 00:16:31,583
How about it you gave
yourself a nickname.

426
00:16:31,666 --> 00:16:32,583
What would it be?

427
00:16:32,666 --> 00:16:34,750
Tsuka-chan? Kasa-chan?

428
00:16:34,833 --> 00:16:37,333
Hmm. How 'bout Hii-chan?

429
00:16:37,416 --> 00:16:39,416
It's hard to make a nickname
out of my first name.

430
00:16:39,500 --> 00:16:41,625
That's perfect! 'Cause I can
picture you as the type

431
00:16:41,708 --> 00:16:43,958
who'd run around shrieking,
"Hihi!" all the time.

432
00:16:44,041 --> 00:16:46,208
That's not exactly
what I meant either.

433
00:16:46,291 --> 00:16:48,416
Right!
From this day forward, Tsukasa,

434
00:16:48,500 --> 00:16:50,625
--I'm calling you Hii-chan.
--Huh?

435
00:16:50,708 --> 00:16:51,916
What? What's wrong?

436
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:54,083
-What do you mean, "huh"?
-[chuckles]

437
00:16:54,166 --> 00:16:56,083
It's just that it's
kinda weird, you know?

438
00:16:56,166 --> 00:16:58,208
Picking your own
nickname, and all.

439
00:16:58,291 --> 00:17:00,416
--Then, how about that?
--That?

440
00:17:00,500 --> 00:17:02,625
Uh. I guess it doesn't matter.

441
00:17:02,708 --> 00:17:04,375
Don't you want
revenge, Sebastian?

442
00:17:04,458 --> 00:17:08,791
--Shiraishi.
--Hey, Kyou-chan! Kyou-chan!

443
00:17:08,875 --> 00:17:11,625
What the heck are you saying?
Are you calling me?

444
00:17:11,708 --> 00:17:13,625
It's totally confusing,
so stop it.

445
00:17:13,708 --> 00:17:16,125
Okay. Then what do you
want me to call you?

446
00:17:16,208 --> 00:17:17,958
Isn't Kagami good enough?

447
00:17:18,041 --> 00:17:19,750
Well, don't you wanna
have a nickname too?

448
00:17:19,833 --> 00:17:22,750
You know, like
Kona-chan and Yuki-chan?

449
00:17:22,833 --> 00:17:24,333
Hmm.

450
00:17:25,416 --> 00:17:27,375
How 'bout Kagami-sama?

451
00:17:27,458 --> 00:17:28,833
Uh.

452
00:17:28,916 --> 00:17:31,000
Hey! Kagami-sama!

453
00:17:31,083 --> 00:17:33,250
Ugh. Oh, no!
She's using it.

454
00:17:33,333 --> 00:17:34,416
Yeah, what?

455
00:17:34,500 --> 00:17:35,791
I was just callin' ya.

456
00:17:37,833 --> 00:17:40,041
Sorry for the wait, Kagami-sama.

457
00:17:40,125 --> 00:17:41,750
What's wrong, Kagami-sama?

458
00:17:41,833 --> 00:17:43,666
[KAGAMI]
I'm sorry. It's my fault.

459
00:17:43,750 --> 00:17:46,458
Just please call me by my name.

460
00:17:47,708 --> 00:17:48,625
[GIRLS]
"Lucky Star."

461
00:17:48,708 --> 00:17:49,958
[cat meows]

462
00:17:50,041 --> 00:17:52,583
[AKIRA]
"Lucky Channel"!

463
00:17:52,666 --> 00:17:54,000
Hi, Luckies!

464
00:17:54,083 --> 00:17:55,666
Wow! Isn't this great?

465
00:17:55,750 --> 00:17:57,375
Can you guys believe
that Lucky Channel's

466
00:17:57,458 --> 00:17:59,708
surging forward
with its tenth episode!

467
00:17:59,791 --> 00:18:03,000
I'm Akira Kogami,
your navigator.

468
00:18:03,083 --> 00:18:05,833
Hello! I'm her assistant,
Minoru Shiraishi.

469
00:18:05,916 --> 00:18:07,333
How 'bout we get
down to business

470
00:18:07,416 --> 00:18:09,208
by introducing
the fourth character.

471
00:18:09,291 --> 00:18:11,250
It's Kagami Hiiragi!

472
00:18:11,333 --> 00:18:12,916
In the show,
she's the one who plays

473
00:18:13,000 --> 00:18:15,000
the rational character
and keeps things on track.

474
00:18:15,083 --> 00:18:17,125
So, basically she's
a tsundere type. Yeah.

475
00:18:17,208 --> 00:18:18,958
Right, I got it. Tsundere.

476
00:18:19,041 --> 00:18:20,416
Talk about a shallow character.

477
00:18:20,500 --> 00:18:21,541
On the contrary.

478
00:18:21,625 --> 00:18:22,708
Huh?

479
00:18:22,791 --> 00:18:24,250
Let's not jump to conclusions

480
00:18:24,333 --> 00:18:26,833
by categorizing Kagami-san
as a mere tsundere.

481
00:18:26,916 --> 00:18:28,416
[snickers]
What is she then?

482
00:18:28,500 --> 00:18:30,875
Before we get into that,
we must ask ourselves,

483
00:18:30,958 --> 00:18:33,625
do we truly grasp
the concept of tsundere?

484
00:18:33,708 --> 00:18:35,375
See, in this day
and age, it's a sad fact

485
00:18:35,458 --> 00:18:36,791
that as the term tsundere

486
00:18:36,875 --> 00:18:38,250
becomes a part
of the main-stream,

487
00:18:38,333 --> 00:18:40,625
its true meaning gets
lost in the process.

488
00:18:40,708 --> 00:18:42,541
First we must trace its origins.

489
00:18:42,625 --> 00:18:45,416
The term tsundere dates
back to the year 2002,

490
00:18:45,500 --> 00:18:47,458
where it was first
used on the Internet.

491
00:18:47,541 --> 00:18:50,083
It meant "a hostile person
who becomes affectionate."

492
00:18:50,166 --> 00:18:52,083
In other words, it was
supposed to describe

493
00:18:52,166 --> 00:18:54,708
how a character's personality
changed over time!

494
00:18:54,791 --> 00:18:56,000
Yeah, whatever.

495
00:18:56,083 --> 00:18:57,791
These days, however,
tsundere is used

496
00:18:57,875 --> 00:18:59,833
to describe
a character's dual nature.

497
00:18:59,916 --> 00:19:01,666
For example, a girl
who's cold on the outside

498
00:19:01,750 --> 00:19:03,500
but loving on the
inside would fit

499
00:19:03,583 --> 00:19:05,125
the current definition
of the term.

500
00:19:05,208 --> 00:19:06,833
I'm gonna go out on a limb here.

501
00:19:06,916 --> 00:19:09,416
I declare that this
is all a huge mistake!

502
00:19:09,500 --> 00:19:10,875
We must give the people back

503
00:19:10,958 --> 00:19:12,666
the true definition of tsundere!

504
00:19:12,750 --> 00:19:14,250
Sound the warning bells!

505
00:19:14,333 --> 00:19:16,416
Rise up and be counted,
you illiterate masses!

506
00:19:16,500 --> 00:19:18,416
Arise!

507
00:19:18,500 --> 00:19:20,166
You were going pretty
good there, Sebastian.

508
00:19:20,250 --> 00:19:21,750
Who's that?

509
00:19:21,833 --> 00:19:23,708
So if Kagami isn't
a tsundere, what is she?

510
00:19:23,791 --> 00:19:25,125
Who's Sebastian?

511
00:19:25,208 --> 00:19:26,500
I don't get why
you're making it harder

512
00:19:26,583 --> 00:19:27,833
than it needs to be, you know?

513
00:19:27,916 --> 00:19:29,208
But since you
brought it up, chief,

514
00:19:29,291 --> 00:19:30,791
you got another word we can use

515
00:19:30,875 --> 00:19:33,041
besides tsundere that gets
the same point across?

516
00:19:33,125 --> 00:19:34,833
What? Oh! Ah. I'm
sure there's somethin'

517
00:19:34,916 --> 00:19:36,166
out there that would work.

518
00:19:36,250 --> 00:19:38,583
Maybe Cool-dere?
No, that's not it.

519
00:19:38,666 --> 00:19:40,125
Deretsun?

520
00:19:40,208 --> 00:19:42,000
You really are an idiot,
did you know that?

521
00:19:42,083 --> 00:19:44,208
Isn't tsundere good enough?

522
00:19:44,291 --> 00:19:47,375
No, it isn't. That's
what I've been saying!

523
00:19:47,458 --> 00:19:49,375
Oh! How 'bout
we have our viewers

524
00:19:49,458 --> 00:19:51,750
think of a new term that
could replace tsundere?

525
00:19:51,833 --> 00:19:54,166
Now, that's what
I call a good idea.

526
00:19:54,250 --> 00:19:55,958
Coward.
[upbeat jazz disco music]

527
00:19:56,041 --> 00:19:58,250
Listen up! This goes out to
everyone watching right now.

528
00:19:58,333 --> 00:20:00,125
I want you to come up
with a new term

529
00:20:00,208 --> 00:20:02,208
that would describe
a character like Kagami.

530
00:20:02,291 --> 00:20:03,583
And together we'll rewrite

531
00:20:03,666 --> 00:20:05,583
the common facts of
modern-day speech.

532
00:20:05,666 --> 00:20:07,583
We'll call it
The Great Tsundere Debate!

533
00:20:07,666 --> 00:20:09,791
For more info, please
check out our radio show

534
00:20:09,875 --> 00:20:11,583
or log on to our site.

535
00:20:11,666 --> 00:20:13,875
We're counting on your ideas!

536
00:20:15,041 --> 00:20:17,833
Uh. So, are we done now?

537
00:20:17,916 --> 00:20:19,333
'Bout freakin' time.

538
00:20:19,416 --> 00:20:22,791
Lots and lots and lots and lots.

539
00:20:23,833 --> 00:20:24,791
Bye-ni.

540
00:20:24,875 --> 00:20:26,500
--Bye-ni!
--[loud trumpets]

541
00:20:26,583 --> 00:20:27,666
Fast forward!

542
00:20:29,125 --> 00:20:31,958
[MINORU]
Wow! I talked up a storm today.

543
00:20:32,041 --> 00:20:33,625
That was the best show ever!

544
00:20:34,958 --> 00:20:37,416
Uh. Akira-sama?

545
00:20:37,500 --> 00:20:38,666
What's wrong?

546
00:20:38,750 --> 00:20:39,916
[AKIRA]
Happy now?

547
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:41,708
[MINORU]
Oh, yeah! I mean...

548
00:20:41,791 --> 00:20:42,916
I got a lot of lines today.

549
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:44,208
I think I did a good job!

550
00:20:44,291 --> 00:20:45,541
[Akira sighs]

551
00:20:45,625 --> 00:20:47,041
[AKIRA]
So, I'm gonna have dinner

552
00:20:47,125 --> 00:20:48,500
with one of the producers
and the president

553
00:20:48,583 --> 00:20:49,666
of the production company.

554
00:20:49,750 --> 00:20:51,708
--[MINORU] Huh? Oh!
--[AKIRA] Yeah.

555
00:20:51,791 --> 00:20:54,125
We're gonna be talking
about your future with the show.

556
00:20:54,208 --> 00:20:55,458
[MINORU]
Hold on a second. Wait!

557
00:20:55,541 --> 00:20:56,791
What's that supposed to mean?

558
00:20:56,875 --> 00:20:58,500
[Akira sighs]

559
00:20:58,583 --> 00:21:00,416
[AKIRA] I don't know if
telling you is gonna help.

560
00:21:00,500 --> 00:21:02,875
I mean, if I have to tell you,
you already don't get it.

561
00:21:02,958 --> 00:21:04,416
--[MINORU] Whoa!
--[AKIRA] You still got that

562
00:21:04,500 --> 00:21:06,166
part time gig in
[bleep], don't you?

563
00:21:06,250 --> 00:21:08,000
[MINORU]
Yeah, like during the day, I do.

564
00:21:08,083 --> 00:21:09,708
But it's not like I'm
getting rich working there.

565
00:21:09,791 --> 00:21:11,250
[AKIRA]
And the Korean barbecue?

566
00:21:11,333 --> 00:21:13,041
[MINORU] Well, yeah,
I work there too, but--

567
00:21:13,125 --> 00:21:14,666
Wait! No!
That doesn't matter!

568
00:21:14,750 --> 00:21:16,416
Just stop it! That's
all private stuff!

569
00:21:20,666 --> 00:21:22,458
[KAGAMI]
Well, here I go.

570
00:21:22,541 --> 00:21:24,500
[KONATA] What do you think
about this song, Tsukasa?

571
00:21:24,583 --> 00:21:26,875
[TSUKASA] Maybe. What do
you think, Yuki-chan?

572
00:21:26,958 --> 00:21:28,583
[MIYUKI]
Yes, I know it.

573
00:21:28,666 --> 00:21:30,166
[KONATA] Then, how 'bout
you guys sing it next?

574
00:21:30,250 --> 00:21:31,541
[TSUKASA]
Thanks for finding it.

575
00:21:31,625 --> 00:21:32,791
[MIYUKI]
Yes, thank you.

576
00:21:32,875 --> 00:21:34,083
[KONATA]
At last.

577
00:21:34,166 --> 00:21:35,416
[KAGAMI]
Did you guys decide on a song?

578
00:21:35,500 --> 00:21:36,875
[TSUKASA]
Yeah!

579
00:21:36,958 --> 00:21:39,583
[KAGAMI singing in Japanese]

580
00:21:41,291 --> 00:21:42,958
[TSUKASA]
Hey! Wasn't this song popular

581
00:21:43,041 --> 00:21:44,500
back when we were
in kindergarten?

582
00:21:44,583 --> 00:21:46,333
[KONATA]
No idea.

583
00:21:46,416 --> 00:21:48,041
[TSUKASA] Oh, I'm sorry.
I don't know either.

584
00:21:48,125 --> 00:21:49,500
[MIYUKI]
I totally remember it.

585
00:21:49,583 --> 00:21:51,333
Our sisters used
to sing it a lot.

586
00:21:51,416 --> 00:21:52,916
[TSUKASA]
It's said that songs sung

587
00:21:53,000 --> 00:21:54,458
by our parents or
older siblings,

588
00:21:54,541 --> 00:21:56,166
even though they're from
a generation before us,

589
00:21:56,250 --> 00:21:59,416
are the ones we
remember the most.

590
00:21:59,500 --> 00:22:02,250
[singing continues]

591
00:22:29,041 --> 00:22:30,958
[KONATA]
Oh! She couldn't hit it.

592
00:22:31,041 --> 00:22:33,625
[KAGAMI] I couldn't help it!
It's too high.

593
00:22:47,833 --> 00:22:50,125
[MAN] On the next episode
of "Lucky Star"!

594
00:22:50,208 --> 00:22:52,250
[KAGAMI] Kagami here!
Say you're out with a friend

595
00:22:52,333 --> 00:22:53,458
and you're getting
